✅ Minikube Installation Steps (Windows)
Step 1: Install Prerequisites
1. Virtualization Support

Ensure virtualization is enabled in BIOS.

Verify in Windows:

systeminfo


Look for: Virtualization Enabled: Yes

2. Install a Hypervisor

Minikube requires a driver/hypervisor:

Hyper-V
(Available in Windows 10/11 Pro/Enterprise)

OR Docker Desktop
(Can be used as --driver=docker)

OR VirtualBox

Step 2: Download Minikube

Open PowerShell or CMD as Administrator

Run:

curl -LO https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-installer.exe


Install Minikube:

.\minikube-installer.exe

Step 3: Add Minikube to PATH (If Needed)

Open System Properties → Environment Variables

Edit PATH

Add:

C:\Program Files\Minikube

Step 4: Start Minikube

Open CMD/PowerShell and run:

Start with your preferred driver

Hyper-V

"minikube start --driver=hyperv"


Docker

minikube start --driver=docker

Verify cluster status
minikube status

Step 5: Interact with Minikube (kubectl)

kubectl is the Kubernetes command-line tool.

Use kubectl provided by Minikube
"minikube kubectl -- get pods -A"

Optional: Minikube Dashboard
"minikube dashboard"

Optional: Verify Installation
minikube version
"kubectl version --client"

Troubleshooting

If Minikube fails to start:

"minikube logs"


Ensure Hyper-V/Docker/VirtualBox is installed and running.

Update Minikube:

"minikube update-check
minikube update"

✅ Minikube Automation: Deployment Steps
Step 1: Start Minikube Cluster
"minikube start"

Step 2: Create and Manage Deployment
Create Nginx deployment
"kubectl create deployment mynginx --image=nginx"

If deployment exists, update image
"kubectl set image deployment/mynginx nginx=nginx:latest"

Verify deployment
"kubectl get deployments
kubectl get pods
kubectl describe pods"

Step 3: Expose Deployment as a Service
"kubectl expose deployment mynginx --type=NodePort --port=80 --target-port=80"

Step 4: Scale Deployment
"kubectl scale deployment mynginx --replicas=4
kubectl get service mynginx"

Step 5: Access NGINX Application
Option 1: Port Forwarding
"kubectl port-forward svc/mynginx 8081:80"


Open in browser:

http://localhost:8081

Option 2: Minikube Tunnel (If port-forward fails)
"minikube tunnel"


Retrieve service URL:

"minikube service mynginx --url"

Open Kubernetes Dashboard
"minikube dashboard"

Step 6: Stop and Clean Up
Delete Deployment & Service
"kubectl delete deployment mynginx
kubectl delete service mynginx"

Stop Minikube
"minikube stop"

Delete Minikube Cluster
"minikube delete"

✅ Nagios Automation Using Docker
Step 1: Pull Nagios Image
"docker pull jasonrivers/nagios:latest"

Step 2: Run Nagios Container
"docker run --name nagiosdemo -p 8888:80 jasonrivers/nagios:latest"

Step 3: Access Nagios Dashboard

Open:

http://localhost:8888

Login Credentials

Username: nagiosadmin

Password: nagios

Dashboard Sections

Hosts

Services

Alerts

Step 4: Host Monitoring Details

Inside Nagios:

Key Information:

Host Status: UP/DOWN

CPU / Memory / Network metrics

Actions: Disable notifications, schedule downtime, etc.

Step 5: Stop and Remove Nagios
Stop container
"docker stop nagiosdemo"

Remove container
"docker rm nagiosdemo"

Remove image (optional)
docker images
docker rmi jasonrivers/nagios:latest

⭐ AWS Free-Tier Account Creation Steps

Open:

https://aws.amazon.com


Click Create AWS Account

Enter email ID and name

Enter verification code received by email

Fill contact details, accept Terms → Click Create

Add billing details → Click Verify and Continue

₹2 is charged for card verification (refunded later)

Add mobile number, select country → Click Send SMS

Enter OTP received on mobile

Select Basic Plan (Free Tier) → Click Complete Sign Up
